\subsection{Percentage vs.\ Absolute Error Trade-off}

An important distinction emerges between objectives:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{Objective} & \textbf{Absolute Error (OOS RMSE)} & \textbf{Relative Error (OOS \%)} \\
\midrule
Vega-Weighted & 0.3923 & 5.45\% \\
Relative & 0.5247 & 3.42\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Trade-off illustration: Vega-weighted minimizes absolute dollar error; Relative minimizes percentage error.}
\end{table}

\textbf{Strategic Choice:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Dollar-based risk management}: Use Vega-Weighted (minimizes absolute P\&L exposure across the portfolio)
    \item \textbf{Percentage-based strategies}: Use Relative (minimizes relative P\&L; preferable for position sizing that scales with option price, e.g., percentage-of-notional hedges)
\end{itemize}

\section{Key Findings}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Robust Calibration}: Generalization gaps near zero ($\pm 0.02$) for Vega-Weighted and Relative indicate the model generalizes well to unseen data.
    
    \item \textbf{Vega-Weighting Wins on Dollars}: \$0.39 OOS RMSE is 25\% better than Relative (\$0.52), making Vega-Weighted the default for dollar-based hedging.
    
    \item \textbf{Relative Wins on Percentages}: 3.42\% relative error vs.\ 5.45\% for Vega-Weighted makes it preferable for strategies with percentage P\&L targets.
    
    \item \textbf{Implied Vol Overfits}: Negative generalization gap and highest parameter volatility disqualify IV as an objective function.
    
    \item \textbf{Parameter Stability}: Relative shows best stability, followed by Vega-Weighted. This suggests these are more robust calibration targets.
\end{enumerate}

